<section xml:id="section-graphing-equations">

    <title>Graphing Equations</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ol>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-label-and-scale-graphs" /></li>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-different-scales" /></li>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-table-of-values" /></li>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-plot-points-from-table" /></li>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-emphasize-graph-visual-representation-of-solution-set" /></li>
             <li><xref ref="mth60-create-graph-linear-model" /></li>
         </ol>
    </objectives>

    <p>We have learned how to plot points in a coordinate system. Next, we will learn how to graph <em>lines</em> and <em>curves</em> that come from equations like <m>y=-2x+5</m> and <m>y=x^2\text{.}</m> What's special about these equations is that they are in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> with only <m>x</m>-variables on the right. That makes them relatively easy to graph with a little bit of patience.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="33kaIpvncag" />
    </figure>

    <p>We are trying to take an equation like <m>y=-2x+3</m> and produce a picture that might look like <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full">Figure</xref>. We're hoping to capture all the ordered pairs that you could substitute in to <m>y=-2x+3</m> and make a true equation, and then shade in those ordered pairs. For several examples, see <xref ref="figure-check-points-for-line">Figure</xref>.</p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-check-points-for-line">
        <caption />
        <p><md>
            <mrow>y\amp=-2x+3\amp\amp(x,y)</mrow>
            <mrow>\hline\highlight{5}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{-1})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{-1},\highlight{5})</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{3}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{0})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{0},\highlight{3})</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{1}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{1})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{1},\highlight{1})</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{-1}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{2})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{2},\highlight{-1})</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{-3}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{3})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{3},\highlight{-3})</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{-5}\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-2(\highlight{4})+3\amp\amp(\highlight{4},\highlight{-5})</mrow>
        </md></p>
    </figure>

    <p><xref ref="figure-check-points-for-line">Table</xref> tells us that the points <m>(-1,5)</m>, <m>(0,3)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m>, <m>(2,-1)</m>, <m>(3,-3)</m>, and <m>(4,-5)</m> are all solutions to the equation <m>y=-2x+3</m>, and so they should all be shaded as part of that equation's graph. You can see them in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-sparse">Figure</xref>. But there are many more points that make the equation true. Some more are marked in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-more">Figure</xref>. Even more are marked in <xref ref="figure-graph-line-full">Figure</xref>; so many that together they form what looks like a straight line.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%">
        <caption>Graphs of the Equation <m>y=-2x+3</m></caption>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-sparse">
            <caption>A few points<ellipsis/></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,5)} node[rotate=30,left]{$(-1,5)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,3)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(0,3)$};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(1,1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(2,-1)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,-3)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(3,-3)$};;
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-5)} node[rotate=30,right]{$(4,-5)$};;
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-more">
            <caption>More points<ellipsis /></caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1.5,6) (-1.2,5.4) (-1,5) (-0.8,4.6) (-0.3, 3.6) (0,3) (0.4,2.2) (1,1) (1.1,0.8) (1.7,-0.4) (2,-1) (2.3,-1.6) (2.6,-2.2) (3,-3) (3.5,-4) (4,-5) (4.3,-5.6) (4.8,-6.6)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="figure-graph-line-full">
            <caption>So many points it looks like a straight line</caption>
            <image>
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[]
                            \addplot+[domain=-2:5,soliddot,samples=50] {-2*x+3};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>So<ellipsis /></p>

    <remark>
        <p>Points are shaded on the graph of an equation exacltly when they make the equation true (when the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values are substituted in).</p>
    </remark>

    <exercise>
        <webwork>
            <setup>
                <pg-code>
