    <exercise>
        <webwork>
            <setup>
                <pg-code>
                    Context()->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                    @y=(-2,-7);
                    @x=(5,-10);
                    Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0);
                    $f=Compute("-(3/5)x+1");
                    @right=map{$f->substitute(x=>Formula($x[$_]))}(0,1);
                    @truefalse=(PopUp(['?','true','false'],1),PopUp(['?','true','false'],2));
                    @shaded=(PopUp(['?','shaded','not shaded'],1),PopUp(['?','shaded','not shaded'],2));
                </pg-code>
            </setup>
            <statement>
                <p>Decide whether the points <m>(5,-2)</m> and <m>(-10,-7)</m> will be on the graph of the equation <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>
                <p>At <m>(5,-2)</m>:</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="right" />
                        <col/>
                        <col/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><var name="$y[0]" width="1" /></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><var name="$right[0]" width="10" /></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>This equation is <var name="$truefalse[0]" form="popup" />, and <m>(5,-2)</m> is <var name="$shaded[0]" form="popup" /> on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m>.</p>
                <p>At <m>(-10,-7)</m>:</p>
                <table>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="right" />
                        <col/>
                        <col/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-\frac{3}{5}x+1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><var name="$y[1]" width="1" /></cell>
                            <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                            <cell><var name="$right[1]" width="10" /></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>This equation is <var name="$truefalse[1]" form="popup" />, and <m>(5,-2)</m> is <var name="$shaded[1]" form="popup" /> on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>If the point <m>(5,-2)</m> is on <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{,}</m> once we substitute <m>x=5</m> and <m>y=-2</m> into the line's equaiton, the equation should be true. Let's try:<md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-\frac{3}{5}(5)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -3+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -2</mrow>
                </md>Because this last equation is true, we can definitively say that <m>(5,-2)</m> is on the graph of <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>However if we substitute <m>x=-10</m> and <m>y=-7</m> into the equation, it leads to <m>-7=7</m>, which is false. This definitively tells us that <m>(-10,-7)</m> is not on the graph.</p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>All of this suggests a way to make our own graphs for equations using a little bit of calculation. All we need to do is make up a list of reasonable <m>x</m>-values, calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot the corresponding points.</p>

    <example>
        <p>Let's plot a graph for the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>. We use a table to organize our work:</p>

        <sidebyside>
            <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
            <table>
                <caption>Set up the table</caption>
                <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                        <cell>Point</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-2)+5=\highlight{9}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-1)+5=\highlight{7}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(0)+5=\highlight{5}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(1)+5=\highlight{3}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="none">
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{-2(2)+5=\highlight{1}}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <table>
                <caption>Complete the table</caption>
                <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                        <cell>Point</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(-2)+5=\highlight{9}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(-1)+5=\highlight{7}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(0)+5=\highlight{5}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(1)+5=\highlight{3}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="none">
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>-2(2)+5=\highlight{1}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>With the points we've made in the table, we can plot the equation's graph. Just plot the points first, and then assume that the complete graph would be the apparent shape that the points are suggesting. In this case, the points are in a straight line.</p>

        <aside>
            <title>Arrowheads</title>
            <p>To communicate that the full graph extends beyond the viewing window we are using, it's good to put arrowheads on your graphs.</p>
        </aside>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
            <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
            <figure>
                <caption>Use points from the table</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                        xtick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        ytick=,
                                        minor ytick=,]
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
                <caption>Connect the points in whatever pattern is apparent</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                        xtick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        ytick=,
                                        minor ytick=,]
                                \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <remark>
        <p>Note that we could have chosen any <m>x</m>-values, and we would get the same graph. If there is no good reason to use other <m>x</m>-values, we often choose integers from <m>-2</m> to <m>2</m>. Those numbers are easy to calculate with. However sometimes the equation comes with context that suggests using other <m>x</m>-values, as in this next example.</p>
    </remark>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Your gas tank holds up to <quantity><mag>14</mag><unit base="gallon" /></quantity>, and on a long road trip, your car uses <quantity><mag>0.032</mag><unit base="gallon"/><per base="mile"/></quantity>. So if you fill your tank and then drive <m>x</m> miles, your tank will still have <m>14-0.032x</m> gallons of gas. In other words the equation <m>y=14-0.032x</m> models this situation. The variable <m>x</m> represents the number of miles driven, and <m>y</m> represents what the amount of gas still in your tank. Build a table and graph for this equation.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Choosing <m>x</m>-values like <m>-2</m> or <m>1</m> seems a bit nonsensical. We won't be driving a negative number of miles, and this is a road trip certainly longer than <m>1</m> mile. Given the context of the problem, let's choose <m>x</m>-values that are more reasonable as a number of miles we might drive in a day.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table>
                    <caption>Make the table</caption>
                    <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell halign="center"><m>y=14-0.032x</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>13.36</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(20,13.36)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>12.4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(50,12.4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>80</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>11.44</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(80,11.44)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>100</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>10.8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(100,10.8)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="none">
                            <cell><m>200</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>7.6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(200,7.6)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Make the graph</caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=0,xmax=250,
                                            ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                            xlabel={$x$ (miles)},
                                            ylabel={$y$ (gallons)},
                                            xtick=,
                                            minor xtick={0,10,...,250},
                                            ytick=,
                                            minor ytick={0,1,...,20},
                                            clip=false,
                                            grid=major,
                                            axis line style={->}]
                                    \addplot+[domain=0:250,->] {14-0.032*x};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(20,13.36)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(20,13.36)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(50,12.4)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(50,12.4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(80,11.44)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(80,11.44)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(100,10.8)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(100,10.8)$};;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(200,7.6)} node[above right,rotate=30]{$(200,7.6)$};;
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <aside>
        <title>Units on axes labels</title>
        <p>In this last example, note how the graph's axes also tell us what units the variables are measured in. Always do this when you are making a graph with context behind it.</p>
    </aside>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Build a table and graph the equation <m>y=x^2\text{.}</m> Use <m>x</m>-values from <m>-3</m> to <m>3</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <table>
                    <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell halign="center"><m>y=x^2</m></cell>
                            <cell>Point</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3)^2=9</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3,9)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)^2=4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2,4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)^2=1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1,1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0)^2=0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,0)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(1)^2=1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(0,1)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(2)^2=4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(2,4)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="none">
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(3)^2=9</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(3,9)</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-3,9), (-2,4),(-1,1),(0,0),(1,1),(2,4),(3,9)</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=10,
                                            ytick=,
                                            minor ytick={-2,-1,...,10},]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-3.16:3.16] {x^2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,9)} node[left]{$(-3,9)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,4)} node[left]{$(-2,4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,1)} node[left]{$(-1,1)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[below]{$(0,0)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,1)} node[right]{$(1,1)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,4)} node[right]{$(2,4)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,9)} node[right]{$(3,9)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>In this example the points did not fall in a straight line, and that's how it goes sometimes. We drew a curve that connected the points moving left to right. This is the correct thing to do, since each <m>x</m>-value on the horizontal axis leads to a single <m>y</m>-value.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

